<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,618,2022]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1961,1986]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authority="Latin" authorityName="Latin" box="[565,740,1961,1986]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa">
<emphasis box="[565,655,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">demissa</emphasis>
(Latin)
</taxonomicName>
meaning dwelling in lowlands, refers to the lowland habitat in which this species has been found. It is used as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289943/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" targetBox="[166,1426,200,1150]" targetPageId="23">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1180,1265]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,333,1180,1203]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">FIGURES 31–33</emphasis>
. Male terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[543,785,1181,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[543,785,1181,1203]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hemerodromia demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[791,904,1181,1203]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[791,872,1182,1203]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
31
</emphasis>
, lateral view of terminalia; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1188,1213,1181,1202]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">32</emphasis>
, dorsal view of cerci; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,176,1212,1233]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">33</emphasis>
, apex of right cercus, inner surface viewed in slightly anterior aspect. Abbreviations: cer = cerci, epa = epandrium, hyp = hypandrium.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,1304,1760]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1304,1329]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[327,599,1304,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[327,599,1304,1329]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hemerodromia demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[612,708,1304,1329]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[612,708,1304,1329]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is clearly closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1058,1184,1305,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis box="[1058,1184,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Yunnan 
<collectingCountry box="[1362,1432,1304,1329]" name="China" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">China</collectingCountry>
, differing mostly in the shape of the distal processes of the cercus and small differences in shape of the tip of the lower epandrial process. 
<taxonomicName box="[438,707,1376,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[438,707,1376,1401]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hemerodromia demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[716,808,1376,1401]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[716,808,1376,1401]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
lacks a deeply serrate margin on the inner face of the cercus distally (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Grootaert" box="[374,614,1412,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refString="Grootaert, P., Yang, D. &amp; Saigusa, T. (2000) Empididae (Diptera: Empidoidea) from Xishuangbanna, Yunnan (I): Hemerodromiinae. Bulletin de L'Institute Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, 70, 71 - 80." type="journal article" year="2000">
Grootaert 
<emphasis box="[490,539,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[555,614,1413,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[672,699,1413,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="11.0">11</number>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Yang" box="[756,977,1413,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refString="Yang, D. &amp; Yang, C. (2004) Diptera: Empididae: Hemerodromiinae, Hybotinae. Fauna Sinica, Insecta, 34, i - x, 1 - 335." type="journal article" year="2004">
Yang &amp; Yang 
<number box="[918,977,1413,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[1035,1077,1413,1437]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="113.0">113</number>
) but instead has a single strong rather pointed, incurved process at the apex (
<figureCitation box="[656,741,1448,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 33" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1180,1203]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,200,1150]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[152,1435,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 33. Male terminalia of Hemerodromia demissa sp. nov. 31, lateral view of terminalia; 32, dorsal view of cerci; 33, apex of right cercus, inner surface viewed in slightly anterior aspect. Abbreviations: cer = cerci, epa = epandrium, hyp = hypandrium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289943/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[709,741,1448,1472]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
). Additionally the downcurved apical process of the cercus in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,272,1485,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis box="[151,272,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather quadrate in lateral view (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Grootaert" box="[715,957,1484,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refString="Grootaert, P., Yang, D. &amp; Saigusa, T. (2000) Empididae (Diptera: Empidoidea) from Xishuangbanna, Yunnan (I): Hemerodromiinae. Bulletin de L'Institute Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, 70, 71 - 80." type="journal article" year="2000">
Grootaert 
<emphasis box="[831,882,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[898,957,1485,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[1017,1045,1485,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="10.0">10</number>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Yang" box="[1103,1326,1485,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refString="Yang, D. &amp; Yang, C. (2004) Diptera: Empididae: Hemerodromiinae, Hybotinae. Fauna Sinica, Insecta, 34, i - x, 1 - 335." type="journal article" year="2004">
Yang &amp; Yang 
<number box="[1267,1326,1485,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[1386,1428,1485,1509]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="112.0">112</number>
) whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[280,405,1520,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[280,405,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[413,504,1520,1545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[413,504,1520,1545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
it is more elongate, has stronger serrations on its posterior margin and its extreme apex is not produced dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[504,637,1556,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 33" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1180,1203]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,200,1150]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[152,1435,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 33. Male terminalia of Hemerodromia demissa sp. nov. 31, lateral view of terminalia; 32, dorsal view of cerci; 33, apex of right cercus, inner surface viewed in slightly anterior aspect. Abbreviations: cer = cerci, epa = epandrium, hyp = hypandrium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289943/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 31, 33</figureCitation>
). The thorax of 
<taxonomicName box="[824,945,1557,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis box="[824,945,1557,1580]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently black (
<bibRefCitation author="Grootaert" box="[1186,1428,1556,1581]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refString="Grootaert, P., Yang, D. &amp; Saigusa, T. (2000) Empididae (Diptera: Empidoidea) from Xishuangbanna, Yunnan (I): Hemerodromiinae. Bulletin de L'Institute Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, 70, 71 - 80." type="journal article" year="2000">
Grootaert 
<emphasis box="[1304,1354,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1370,1428,1557,1581]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) whereas it is more reddish brown or reddish black in 
<taxonomicName box="[750,875,1592,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[750,875,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[883,973,1592,1617]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[883,973,1592,1617]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The preapical abdominal segments of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. demissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[251,343,1628,1653]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[251,343,1628,1653]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are distinctly yellow, contrasting with much darker segments on the rest of the abdomen. The species is known from lowland (
<quantity box="[514,644,1664,1689]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.409999999999999" metricValueMax="6.62" metricValueMin="6.2" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="641.0" valueMax="662.0" valueMin="620.0">620–662 m</quantity>
) deciduous and dry evergreen forest biotopes in Chiang Mai Province, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[257,357,1700,1725]" name="Thailand" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[376,465,1700,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 82 – 90" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1913,1936]" captionTargetBox="[292,1274,205,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[277,1305,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 82 – 90. Distribution of Hemerodromia spp. in Thailand at a resolution of 0.25 ° and symbols sized to 0.5 ° of latitude and longitude. 82, H. demissa sp. nov.; 83, H. epsilutea sp. nov.; 84, H. etalutea sp. nov.; 85, H. flaviventris Yang &amp; Yang; 86, H. furcata Grootaert, Yang &amp; Saigusa; 87; H. fusca Yang &amp; Yang; 88, H. gammalutea sp. nov.; 89, H. isochita sp. nov.; 90, H. namtokhinpoon sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289960/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[433,465,1701,1725]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="82.0">82</number>
</figureCitation>
). Adults were captured in February, March and May, coincident with the cool dry season.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
